participants: Sarah Hallahan | Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition > Brian Cullinan | wizard
message:
Hi Brian,

I misunderstood your message so probably took it a tad personal. Are you looking for new career opportunities? If so, we can hop on a call. 

I tend to ask more about motivation, ideal working environment, projects you're proud of and dive deeper into that to get a sense if our working culture and environment and dev lifecycle will be a good fit. 

Let me know if you're interested in a chat.

Thanks,
Sarah
title: Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition

participants: Brian Cullinan | wizard > Sarah Hallahan | Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition
message: Sure I became interested in this conversation because of your job function stated on linked in "building the recruiting function". Maybe I don't understand what that means but I was just wondering if you had considered the option of using chatbots for recruiting? Do you think my resume is too colorful?
title: wizard

participants: Sarah Hallahan | Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition > Brian Cullinan | wizard
message: Ah - I have to update my headline. Perhaps optimising is a better word for now. To be honest, haven't thought of chatbots. I've noticed a trend of people preferring to be on the phone with people from our company to learn more and get a sense of vibe and culture. With regard to the colours, it was eye-catching but understanding the key and how you're using the color schema takes quite a few seconds. it doesn't help for a quick scan if that makes sense.
title: Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition

participants: Brian Cullinan | wizard > Sarah Hallahan | Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition
message: That makes sense. How have you optimized? I see a lot of problems. Like just the other day I was screened out because I answered a combined question on whether I am able to relocate. Are you reading PDFs in an OCR way? I guess I initially started this thread with the thinking that every company wants to ask questions based on what I know or talk about what their company does, very few recruiters actually ask what do I want to accomplish.
title: wizard

participants: Sarah Hallahan | Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition > Brian Cullinan | wizard
message: My first couple of questions for anyone is 1) why are they interested in chatting and what do they want to gain form the call and then 2) if they could craft their ideal role and write their own JD, what would it be. I want to make sure what people want is aligned with what we can offer. Not many recruiters fill roles with a view to retention and best fit. As a candidate, speaking to a recruiter who cares about your interests is a good way to weed out good recruiters from those focused on just filling roles. Unfortunately good recruiters are hard to find and as a result so many hiring practices in companies are very flawed. We're not perfect either but we're working on it.
title: Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition

participants: Brian Cullinan | wizard > Sarah Hallahan | Manager, Technical Talent Aquisition
message: Wow. I wish more people had your insight. Good questions.
title: wizard
